defaultOur answers to the Committee’s questions are as follows:
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat types of CCS technology are currently being developed and how do they differ from one another?default&#xa0;
default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are currently three main technology options for capturing CO2: pre-combustion, post-combustion and oxy-combustion. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default10.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTwo of the partners in the White Rose project - 
defaultAlstom
default and 
defaultLinde
default (BOC) – have already participated in a number of pilot projects:
default&#xa0;
defaultAlstomdefault: projects using oxy-combustion, chilled ammonia, advanced amines or second-generation technologies. 
defaultFive units
default have completed tests in the USA &amp; Europe; while 
defaulteight units are in operation or in commissioning.
default&#xa0;
defaultLindedefault (BOC):default has built an advanced amines-based pilot plant and an oxy-combustion related pilot plant in Germany and is involved as part of a consortium de
defaultveloping a potential pre-combustion plant in the USA.
default&#xa0;
default11.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe pilot and validation plants have shown that the technology works. The next step is to establish the commercial credentials of the technology at large-scale with full CCS chain. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat defaultcontribution could CCS make towards the UK’s decarbonisation targets? Are the UK Government’s expectations reasonable in this regard?default&#xa0;
default12.
default&#xa0; 
defaultPower generation accounts for approximately a third of the UK’s CO2 emissions, or 182 million tonnes of CO2 a year (DECC
default 2013)
default&#xa0;
default Capturing and storing that carbon could reduce emissions from fossil fuel power stations by as much as 95%
default (ETI, 2013). As the Prime Minister said in a recent Liaison Committee meeting: 
default&#xa0;
default‘
defaultdecarbonisation targets only really make sense when you 
defaultknow what is going to be possible in terms of carbon capture and storage….
default If not, you are in quite serious water, because you would be only relying on nuclear and renewable.’ 
default(Liaison Committee, 11 December 2012)
default&#xa0;
default13.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAnalysis
default 
defaultby the Government and the Commi
defaultttee for Climate Change shows that up to 0.6 GW of CCS could be delivered in the UK by 2020; 5-10 GW by 2030 and up to 40 GW by 2050. The CCS Association has argued that 20–30 GW is possible by 2030. The exact number will depend in large part on the succes
defaults of the current Commercialisation Programme and whether the first two projects, including adequately sized initial CO2 transport and storage infrastructure, can be delivered on time.
default&#xa0;
default14.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWith the expected growth of intermittent renewable generation (rising 
defaultfrom 9% of electricity today to 32% by 2030) and the continued contribution of inflexible nuclear generation, it will be important for the UK to maximise the use of flexible, fossil fuel generation. CCS can be designed to enable that flexibility to be real
defaultised, whilst ensuring emissions are reduced effectively.   
default&#xa0;
default15.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn the longer term, CCS combined with biomass is the only low carbon technology that could remove industrial quantities of CO2 from the atmosphere and permanently store it in deep geological for
defaultmations. CO2 is absorbed from the atmosphere during the natural growth process of biomass. Following combustion of the biomass the CO2 is captured and permanently stored providing a net carbon removal from the atmosphere, or ‘negative emissions’. These neg
defaultative emissions could be used to offset emissions from other harder to decarbonise 
defaultsectors. This view was strongly supported by the Committee on Climate Change’s 
defaultBioenergy
default Review (2012). 
default&#xa0;
defaultAre there any potential benefits (e.g. the ability to export CCS tdefaultechnology abroad) of successfully developing CCS to the UK economy and, if so, what are they?default&#xa0;
default16.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Government’s CCS Roadmap estimated benefits of between £3-6.5 billion a year by the late 2020s to UK-based firms, sustaining between 70,000-100,000 jobs.
default 
default&#xa0;
default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA report by CO2Sense (October 2012) estimated that the development of a CCS cluster in Yorkshire &amp; Humberside could provide a major boost to the UK economy, delivering £1.3bn and 4,000 skilled-jobs.
default&#xa0;
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe report stated that ‘Yorkshire and Humber is the be
defaultst strategic location in Europe to build a CCS cluster’ and that ‘putting this funding into the region will increase the area’s economic output by 0.8% per year, attract as much as £11billion in foreign investment and a further 11,000 jobs’.  The cluster w
defaultould also have the potential to make a sizeable reduction to the UK’s carbon emissions by transforming one of the UK's highest emitting regions.
default&#xa0;
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Energy Technologies Institute has estimated that the deployment of CCS at scale could cut the UK’s cost o
defaultf meeting climate targets by around 1% of GDP, equivalent to £30–40 billion annually in 2050. (ETI, Mobilising Private Sector Financing report) 
default&#xa0;
default20.
default&#xa0; 
defaultEnhanced hydrocarbon recovery (EHCR) could also deliver benefits to the UK in terms of energy security, balan
defaultce of payments, tax revenues, deferred decommissioning costs and increased employment as well as helping to move CCS down the cost reduction curve.
