default&#xa0;
defaultWhat are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation if CCS fails?default&#xa0;
default29.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAt the national level, the Energy Technologies Institute has concluded that: 
default&#xa0;
default‘Without a national CCS infrastructure, the cost of reaching UK Climate Change targets will double from a minimum of around £30bn per year in 2050. This is the equivalent of an additional 2p per kWh on all UK energy use in 2050. Therefore the economic priz
defaulte of CCS to the UK is potentially considerable. Our calculations show that each five years of delay in implementing CCS until 2030 will add the equivalent of £4bn per annum to the total cost of the compliant UK energy system’.
default&#xa0;
default30.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 2030 scenarios in DECC’
defaults Delivery Plan (July 2013) show that if CCS is not commercially available by then, the UK will need greater contributions primarily from nuclear and offshore wind. There has to be question marks over whether those technologies could deliver at the require
defaultd higher scale, at a reasonable cost to the taxpayer and provide enough generation flexibility.  
default&#xa0;
default31.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Committee’s letter to the Secretary of State (30 November 2011) sums up the position very well:
default&#xa0;default‘…CCS is a vital technology for the low-carbon 
defaulttransition. There would be serious international and economic implications if we were not able to make this technology available. Without it, we may face an impossible trade-off between our environmental objectives and energy security.’
default&#xa0;
defaultBackground about defaultCapture Powerdefault&#xa0;
default32.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe White Rose partners – 
defaultAlstom
default, 
defaultDrax
default and BOC – are planning to build a 426MW oxy-combustion carbon capture and storage (CCS) demonstration project. The project will comprise a state-of-the-art coal-fired power station that will be equippe
defaultd with full CCS technology. It will be built at the existing 
defaultDrax
default power station site, near Selby, North Yorkshire, and will capture around 90% of emissions. Around two million tonnes of CO
default2
default will be transported through the proposed National Grid pipeline fo
defaultr permanent undersea storage in the North Sea. 
